Woke up at 2.30am feeling like I'd been knocked down by a bus and shivering uncontrollably. Really rather like a HUGE flareup of my Fibromyalgia. Tylenol didn't really help. Tossed and turned until 6am at which point I decided a cup of tea would be nice, especially as I couldn't stop shivering. Plus some stronger pain meds (Tylenol #3, which I usually take at bedtime to help get full and restful sleep). Put day clothes on for warmth and returned to bed. Finally able to get back to sleep around 9am.  Day 2: spent most of the day in bed trying to get/keep warm in order to overcome the extreme whole-body pain. Only got up to get hot drinks and to eat something. Brain fog meant I couldn't concentrate on doing anything. Slept a lot.  Day 3: Feeling MUCH better. My arm was a bit swollen and painful at the site of the shot. The body still felt like it had been in a boxing match and I was a tad sluggish, but the aches and pains were nowhere near as bad as the day before.  Day 4: Most of the strong adverse symptoms were gone, except for milder pain and brain fog.  Day 5: Now almost back to what constitutes 'normal' for me. Back to regular life but with plenty of rest as I find myself getting tired after moderate exertion.

On Sunday afternoon, March 14, I received the first dose of the Pfizer vaccination. On the morning of March 16 I had a sudden hit of fatigued and my left leg started going numb while doing some menial work in the yard, The numbness cleared when I went inside and laid down but some form of the fatigue persisted for several days. Then, on March 28, two weeks after the vaccine, I woke up to a leg severely swollen from toe to hip. I waited two days to see if it went down but it only got worse, swelling to double the size by volume. I went to the doctor and they sent me to the hospital for ultrasound, suspecting a blood clot. No blood clot was evident but there were multi swollen limp nodes in the upper leg area. The problem worsened and two days later I was sent in for a CTscan which now showed multi blood clots near the swollen limp nodes. I was barely able to walk as major pain persisted with no signs of decline. I am now on blood thinner. It has been 2 months since the vacination and my leg is still swollen the same amount (2X by volume).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I noticed immediately that the shot hurt, and that it was almost as if I could feel both the beginning and end of the needle. This was unusual for me, because I don't usually notice pain with vaccines. (It may also be worth nothing that the vaccine was not as centered on the deltoid as usual; it seemed to be injected in a location more anterior than medial.) 36 hours later, while my arm was above my head doing my hair, I suddenly felt a sharp and painful tingling shoot down my arm, with pins-and-needles and numbness. The sensation reached from the top of my arm down the outside around the elbow and heavily culminated in my hand and fingers, especially pinky finger. This sensation somewhat subsided, but lasted for somewhere between 1 and 2 hours.  Since then,  I have experienced pain in my elbow, and sometimes hand/palm and shoulder, and weakness in my hand, fingers, and arm in general. I have described all the different feelings of it as the different stages of having hit your funny bone.
OTHER_MEDS: Vyvanse 60mg Zyrtec 10 mg (may have taken 81 mg aspirin)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Prior to administration of Janssen Covid-19 vaccine the patient was anxious but was completely fine once the procedure commenced and concluded. After finishing explaining the possible side effects of the vaccine and handing the patient the V-Safe handout, she got up slowly and proceeded to our designated post vaccination monitoring seating arrangement. Upon concluding the vaccination process with the patient?s partner, she alerted the pharmacist that she does not feel well. To which he asked her to further elaborate on what she is experiencing. She began to say she thinks she?s going to faint as she is attempting to drink water. As she was having a drink of water she fainted. To which he responded by running over and catching her before she hit the ground, cradling her upper torso, specifically the head and laid her down on the floor with the assistance of pharmacist and her partner. In the midst of everything he instructed another pharmacy technician to call 911 for the paramedics. As she was in the process of drinking water I saw her other hand go to the region of the neck, thinking it was also an allergic reaction and administered a dose of Epi-Pen. He administered the Epi-Pen on the upper side of her thigh, directly to the skin not through clothing. There was a very brief moment where the patient began to convulse but gradually regain consciousness. The patient became lucid and was conversing with him, apologizing for the incident. He assured her there was nothing to apologize for and to which she told me she had similar incidents from vaccinations as a child. She did not mention this prior to administration of the vaccine and through conversation we believe the incident may be caused from high anxiety of needles / vaccinations. When the paramedics arrived, they assisted the patient from the floor and gave a warning that she believed she was going to faint again, and fainted in the arms of the paramedics.
LAB_DATA: Patient went to hospital for further evaluation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: No immediate ill effects after this second shot of the Moderna vaccine at 10 am. Worked that day and went home, woke up around 2 am with sweats and nausea and headache which became progressively worse through the day prohibiting any activity. Dry heaves and severe headache with dizziness lasted until 4 pm or so. I did take Ondansetron at 12 noon to limit nausea. Worked the following day with few physical symptoms but very irritable. The next day (Saturday) woke with headache and slight nausea which became worse as the day wore on, limiting activity but I was able to get chores done, though I was very lethargic. The next day was much better. Worked on Monday the 12th of April and felt well. Fell ill again with similar but less severe symptoms, though marked nausea and dry heaving again. Slept until approximately 2pm and started writing this report. 4/13/2021
LAB_DATA: I contacted my doctor on the really bad day, he replied quickly that NSAIDS and hydration will allow the symptoms to self resolve. I am concerned that some continuing symptoms may need to be reported as they feel to be caused by the vaccine.
OTHER_MEDS: 75 mg CBD, .25 mg Montelukast, 500 mg Acetominophen,

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This literature marketed report has been received from authors of the literature article. Acute gastroenteritis (AGE) in hematopoietic cell transplant (HCT) patients caused significant morbidity and mortality. Data regarding the longitudinal assessment of infectious pathogens during symptomatic AGE and asymptomatic periods, particularly in children, were limited. This article investigated the prevalence of AGE-associated infectious pathogens in children undergoing allogeneic HCT.  This report referred to a child of unknown age and gender. Information about medical history, concurrent condition and concomitant therapy was unknown.   On an unknown date, the patient vaccinated with 1 dose of rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ) (strength, lot# and expiration date were unknown) orally for prophylaxis.  On an unknown date (reported as more than 2 years after 1 dose of rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ)), the patient underwent HCT (inappropriate schedule of product administration). On an unknown date, the patient performed rotavirus test, however, rotavirus was not identified by real-time reverse-transcriptase polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) from the 2 specimens that tested positive by multiplex PCR, which may represent a false positive or low-level shedding.   A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Death Narrative: Patient had Pfizer COVID vaccine dose #1 on 3/20/21. He called his provider on 3/30 to report known exposure to COVID that occurred on 3/27 and 3/28. On 4/1 he tested positive for COVID swabbed at the facility and sent to the main facility for processing. He was notified of positive result on 4/1 at 4pm. He was advised to quarantine and to call facility call center/triage should he develop any fever, shortness of breath, and other Covid-related symptoms. Provider received a phone call from PD on 4/8 notifying of patient unattended death. According to EMS report neighbors were aware of patients COVID positive status. No one had seen or heard from the patient in 3 days so they contacted PD for wellness check. Entry was forced into apartment and patient was found deceased, sitting on the couch. Not breathing ashen color. Pt has ringer and no Pulse. PMH: Quit tobacco 5-15 yrs ago Hyperlipidemia Hyperglycemia Obesity Allergic rhinitis, stable Hx AAA and Right ICA aneurysm, S/P Open repair in 2013 Patient had no prior history of COVID before 4/1 diagnosis. He was not having any symptoms between 4/1 when he tested positive and he did not call to report any symptoms between 4/1 diagnosis and death. There was no communication after 4/1 positive covid test. Patient was scheduled for a phone call with RN on 4/8 the date he was found deceased. Cause of death is not mentioned, but suspected to be due to COVID infection. There were no reported side effects to COVID Vaccine administration.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: FAINTING; DIZZINESS; VOMITING; NAUSEA; This spontaneous multiple patient report was received from physicians, consumer, media, and press release and concerned 11-13 adult male and female patients. Initial information received from a consumer on 07-APR-2021 was processed with additional information received from media and then obtained via follow up with physicians on 08-APR-2021, and from the physician and Department of Public Health and Environment press release on 09-APR-2021.  The patients' height and weight were not reported. The patients' concurrent conditions included anxiety and fainting. The patients received COVID-19 VACCINE AD26.COV2.S (suspension for injection, route of administration, dose, and site of vaccination not reported, batch number: 18008980 and 201A21A) administered on 07-APR-2021 for prophylactic vaccination. No concomitant medications were reported.  On 07-APR-2021, within 15 minutes of vaccination, 11-13 patients out of about 1700 who were vaccinated that day experienced varying symptoms including fainting, dizziness, vomiting, and nausea. The patients received vaccine at a "drive-up" vaccination event, then drove to a parking lot to wait for about 15 minutes with instructions to honk if they felt ill. Two or three patients were transported by EMS to the local hospital for observation. They were later released from the emergency department and were not admitted. Two patients were recommended to go to the hospital, but declined, and were observed and treated with juice and water along with other 7 patients at the site. The reporting physician did not feel that the reactions were due to the lot or the specific vaccine, but were rather due to vasovagal reactions. The press release stated that "the Food and Drug Administration has run the two lot numbers used at the site and found no worrying pattern of similar events with these lots." The action taken with COVID-19 VACCINE AD26.COV2.S was not applicable. The outcome of the fainting, nausea, dizziness, and vomiting was not reported. This case is associated to product complaint PQMS# 90000175639. This case is linked as same patient to 20210415071. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition).; Sender's Comments: V0 This report concerns multiple patients who experienced adverse events after receiving an injection at a "drive-up" vaccination site. On 07-APR-2021, within 15 minutes of vaccination, 11-13 patients out of about 1700 who were vaccinated that day experienced varying symptoms including fainting, dizziness, vomiting, and nausea. Two (or three) patients were transported to the hospital for observation. It was reported that some patients had concurrent anxiety and fainting. Given the close temporal relationship and the nature of the events, the events are considered possibly related to the vaccination, the "Drive-up" circumstance likely were a significant contributory factor.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: DVT; PULMONARY EMBOLISM; KIDNEY BLEEDING; This spontaneous report was received from a physician, and concerned an adult male patient (greater than 50 years old).  Initial report was processed along with additional information received on 12-APR-2021. The patient's weight, height, and medical history were not reported. The patient received Covid-19 vaccine AD26.Cov2.S (suspension for injection, intramuscular, batch number was not reported) dose and site of vaccination were not reported, administered on 20-MAR-2021 for prophylactic vaccination. No concomitant medications were reported. On an unspecified date in 2021, the patient experienced deep vein thrombosis (DVT), pulmonary embolism (PE), and kidney bleeding. The patient was admitted to the hospital and was treated with heparin as well as an inferior vena cava (IVC) filter (put in after he experienced bleeding from his kidney). Laboratory data included: a negative COVID-19 virus test, and throughout hospitalization his platelet count (NR: not provided) was normal: 191,000 and 264,000 (units not provided). The patient's test came back positive for one copy of the Factor V Leiden mutation which predisposed him to blood clots. On 12-APR-2021, the patient was to start a trial to Lovenox (enoxaparin sodium); they will assure there is no bleeding, prior to discharge. At the time of this report, the patient was still hospitalized but doing well.  Action taken with Covid-19 vaccine AD26.Cov2.S was not applicable. The patient was recovering from DVT, pulmonary embolism, and kidney bleeding. This report was serious (Hospitalization Caused / Prolonged, and Other Medically Important Condition).; Sender's Comments: v0 An adult (greater than 50 years old) male patient with a past medical history remarkable for the Factor V Leiden mutation experienced deep vein thrombosis, pulmonary embolism, and kidney bleeding on an unspecified date after receiving Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine Ad26.COV2.S.  The patient was admitted to the hospital and was treated with heparin as well as an inferior vena cava (IVC) filter (put in after he experienced bleeding from his kidney). The patient had a negative COVID-19 virus test, and throughout hospitalization his platelet count was normal: 191,000 and 264,000 (units not provided). The Factor V Leiden mutation is known to predispose patients to venous thrombosis, therefore the causality for deep vein thrombosis, pulmonary embolism as well a consequent kidney bleeding most likely due to heparin treatment is assessed not related to the vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Started experiencing wheezing and shortness of breath and reduction of oxygen level below 90 prior to entering the ER on Sunday, March 21, 2021. Also had severe stomach pain which was determined to be caused by gall bladder stone.

Also performed ultrasound on gall bladder and liver which was clear as well as ultrasound on legs to check for any further blood clots -- none were found in the legs.  ER doctors thought might have been caused by vein procedure on right leg and road trip 10 days later; but in meeting with cardiologist Monday, April 12, and vascular surgeon Monday, April 5, was determined blood clots of this nature would not be indicative of this type of vein procedure.  Further,  all doctors felt quantity and size of blood clots very unusual.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: All regular side effects on day 1 + day 2. (Fever, chills, bone and muscle aches, headache). Shortness of breath started the next day on Sunday , extreme, far beyond normal asthma or any asthma attack. Went to urgent care on Tuesday- they said it was likely a side effect of j &J and tested me for COVID, kidney disease other things, all came back negtative. Apparently I wasn?t the first person they had seen with shortness of breath. Blood in cough and spit on Wednesday after 2.5 days of  shortness of breath. Dizziness (extreme) throughout and chest pain, sternum hurt, chest tightness. Went to Er. They ran a lot of tests and they too said they had seen others with shortness of breath from j and j. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Vaccine was administered and two minutes later patient reported to feel "weird." She kneeled over and started to breathe heavy. Pharmacist was asking if the patient is okay and the patient stopped responding so the pharmacist kneeled over to pick up the patients head and she looked flushed, her eyes were bulging and she began to sweat. The pharmacist asked the technician to call 911, asked the patient if she could breathe and the patient said yes but said she is not feeling well. She kneeled back over and the pharmacist was holding her hand telling her to continue breathing. The patient was very sweaty continued to breathe heavily. About two minutes passed and the patient was expressing she was feeling better and better as the pharmacist was speaking to her. The EMTs arrived 7 minutes after the call the patient had sat up already and was speaking and feeling alert.  She expressed that she felt like she was underwater and the pharmacists voice was fading during the minutes after the shot and she felt like her heart was racing. She explained that she suffers from anxiety.  The EMTs took her blood pressure when the patient was sitting and standing up, blood pressure was in normal range and also checked her blood glucose with a finger stick which was also in normal range. The patient had mentioned previously that she biked to the pharmacy. Later on the pharmacist called to check on the patient she said that she is feeling well and biked back home.

At the time of the shot, I was 16 weeks pregnant. The estimated date of delivery is 13 September.  Approximately 8 hours  after taking the shot, which was administered between 1100-1130 am, I experienced pain in my Left arm. The following morning I was unable to lift my arm and I felt like I had "brain fog" or as if I was fighting a head cold. In the afternoon, I had to sit down after standing for about 10 minutes because I felt like I was getting dizzy and I was nauseated. Typically, I have been nauseated in the mornings because of my pregnancy, and this symptom does not usually effect me in the afternoons. Symptoms were gone the following day.

The adverse symptoms I experienced were abnormally severe/heavy menstrual bleeding and abdominal pain. I was on Day 4 of my menstrual cycle on the day of my injection (April 3, 2021). My menstrual cycle usually starts to go away on Day 4 and concludes by Day 7. But the day after my injection, in addition to experiencing the common side effects of fever, chills, aches, and headaches, I also experienced an uptick in bleeding, which included severe/heavy menstrual bleeding with very frequent and large blood clots. That same day (April 4), I started my new birth control cycle as prescribed. By Day 8 (April 7, 2021), my menstrual bleeding continued to be so severe/heavy that I went to my OB-GYN for testing. The OB-GYN ruled out everything but the vaccine as an environmental factor. It was suggested that I take 600mg of Motrin every 6-hours for 48 hours. My menstrual bleeding continued for several more days until concluding on Day 12 (April 11, 2021) but I am still experiencing abdominal pain.
LAB_DATA: Transvaginal ultrasound and pelvic exam on April 7, 2021.
OTHER_MEDS: Simpesse birth control; vitamin D supplement; vitamin B12 supplement; probiotic; psyllium husk capsules.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: A delayed allergic-type reaction of painful, red, itchy, swollen, firm rash developed on left arm at injection site, 8 days post injection. Large rash roughly the size of an adult hand, wrapping around the lateral aspect of left biceps area at injection site. A little online research told me this is called "Covid Arm" and is a delayed allergic reaction that has been reported in about 1% of people (mostly women) after having their covid-19 vaccine injection. Has been reported almost exclusively with Moderna vaccine. This is not considered a severe reaction and is not reason to delay or my cancel second vaccine dose.  Treated with 400mg Ibuprophen for pain and 50 mg benadryl for itchiness, both taken x 2 per day for 5 days. Also treated topically with hydrocortisone cream for first 2 days of rash. Rash resolved completely by 17 days post injection (4/13/2021). I plan to continue with my second dose of the Moderna vaccine as scheduled, but take ibuprophen and benadryl ahead of the injection and also get the injection in my other (right) arm.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitafusion daily women's multivitamin;  daily Vitafusion 500mg calcium + 25mg D3; daily Vitafusion 50mg D3; daily 2.5mg melatonin
HISTORY: exercise-induced asthma; plantar fasciitis; mild acne

PT SPO2 reading 98% on room air with respirations 18 and regular with clear lung sounds. PT no longer having Shortness of breath or dizziness. PT no longer sweating and he is beginning to stabilize. Radial pulse palpable again and strong and regular at a rate of 76 bpm. PT blood pressure reading 110/76. Upon fire department arrival determined that the PT was stable enough to sit upright in the chair again. PT was assisted off the floor and to a seated position in a chair. PT vitals after seated position for 5-7 min, BP 120/82, pulse 86 strong and regular, RR 20 and clear equal bilateral lung sounds. PT has no other complaints at this time. PT has no allergies to medication, PT has a pollen allergy that he takes over the counter allergy medicines for. PT has no past medical history. Client received the COVID vaccine (Pfizer dose 2, lot #ER8731, expiration date 07/2021) at 1050. Client reported feeling hot, seeing spots, and having a "pounding heart" right as she got vaccinated. EMT and RN responded at 1055. The client appeared flushed and diaphoretic. Vital signs were blood pressure 125/95, heart rate 120, O2 96%, respiratory rate 16. The client denied any shortness of breath or dizziness. The client has no allergies, her only medical condition is anxiety, and her only medications are her birth control and xanax as needed. The client stated they did not take any xanax previous to their appointment. The client stated that they did eat breakfast that day. The client was sitting in her chair comfortably in no distress. They refused benadryl at this time. At 1100, vital signs were as follows: heart rate 115, respiratory rate 14, and O2 95%. The client was alert and oriented, and denied needing any water. She stated that her symptoms were resolved and she was feeling "back to normal." At 1105, the vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 118/82, heart rate 97, respiratory rate 16, O2 99%. Education provided regarding emergency management and AMR activation, v-safe, and primary care follow up. At 1120, the client finished their 30 minute observation, and stated they had no remaining symptoms. Their color had returned to normal and they were no longer diaphoretic. They were able to stand and ambulate without any dizziness. Final vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 120/92, heart rate 92. The client was escorted to their car by the EMT, ambulated with a steady gait.

Patient was with Medical Examiner.  She was reviewing his allergies (PCN, bee stings) and discussed with patient need to wait 30 minutes after vaccine for observation.  She then gave him pfizer vaccine.  Within 1 minute of giving vaccine, patient began to have seizure.  He was assisted to ground by MD and RNs at vaccination site.  He was assessed and assisted to remain safe throughout seizure, 911 called and arrived on scene.  Meanwhile, caregiver with patient stated seizures are "normal" for him and he has 4-5 a day.  She reported that in line he was not feeling well and had precursors to seizure.  Patient had reported to MD that he felt fine today and did not report seizure history to her previous to giving vaccine.  It was also later reported that he had a seizure the night before as well.   IVF were started by RN's.   When emergency services arrived, patient was recovering and refusing to go to ER - against medical advice.  He was assisted back into wheelchair by emergency services personnel.  Patient was alert, and oriented and able to make decision not to go to emergency room.  Patient left facility with caregiver in private vehicle.  Patient was instructed to contact his primary care physician and let them know what happened and ask if 2nd dose of pfizer is appropriate for him.  Patient was also instructed if MD wants him to get 2nd dose to go to a more controlled setting then Mass vaccination site.

My brain/mind were not functioning properly - to the point that I could hardly remember my name, let alone do anything on the computer that I was attempting to do.  At about that same time, I had a feeling of near complete exhaustion come over me, to the point of thinking I might faint at any moment. I went to my bedroom and laid down.  I fell asleep shortly there after and woke up approx 2.5 hours later.  After waking, I felt normal again.  I was able to process my thoughts and did not feel faint or exhausted any more.  It has been 1 month today since having the shot.  I have not felt any additional adverse affects to this point, other than the several hours after the shot. On a side note, I had not been sick prior to the shot or in the several months leading up to the shot.  I have also not been sick since the shot.  It was only the several hours on the day of the shot.
OTHER_MEDS: Metformin, Glimepiride, Lisinopril, Atorvastatin, Gabapentin, Metoprolol
HISTORY: Diabetes type 2, High blood pressure, High cholesterol, Obesity, Nuropathy

Situation Patient called the COVID-19 Nurse Holtine with post-dose vaccine related symptoms/guidance. Pt called PCP office after hearing several news regarding J & J  Vaccine/side effects. Pt was advised to call Nurse Hotline.   Noted from pt's PCP notes from today 4/13/21: "has some anxiety at baseline."  Background Patient received her J & J on 3/7/21 on the left arm.  Number of days post vaccine (today's date minus vaccine date): 6  Initial reaction was noted on : 1 day post vaccine: 3/8/21 around 8 or 9 am.   Symptom Screening  c/o Bilateral leg "achiness."  Pt rated pain 5 out of 10 on the pain scale. Pt denies any hives, itchiness, wheezing, swollen lips, tongue, eyes, difficulty breathing. Chest tightness/pain. Denies any swelling, redness, or itchiness to the both injection sites and to BLE. Pt denies numbness and tingling on the bilateral toes. Pt denies bilateral calf pain.  Pt was able to ambulate without any difficulties.  Medication:  Pt took one dose of  OTC Aleve at 5pm at 3/8 with a good effect.  Pt back to baseline until today.   Pt denies any unusual changes. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my first dose of the Pfizer COVID vaccine last Thursday (4/8) at 9am. I did not have any immediate side effects -- just mild soreness at the injection site in my right arm approximately 8 hours later (I'm left-handed), which subsided by the next morning. However, at approximately 3am on Friday (4/9), I woke up with a fair amount of discomfort in all of the fingers in my left (dominant) hand. It felt like what I would imagine someone suffering from arthritis might feel; I got up to take some ibuprofen and I had difficulty grasping the doorknob, for example. The pain mostly subsided by the time I woke back up, although there was some very minor continued stiffness in my left index finger, which also eventually seemed to go away after a few days.  Fast forward to this morning (4/13) and I woke up around 5am with renewed discomfort and stiffness in my left index finger, requiring ibuprofen. It is now ~3:45pm and the discomfort remains slightly, but has mostly subsided. I should add that I've never experienced this before the vaccine, and I cannot think of anything I did differently in the last week other than receiving the first dose of the Pfizer vaccine.  I reported this event today to my primary care physician, but have not sought additional treatment.
OTHER_MEDS: Country Life Acerola Vitamin C complex supplement, Nature's Way sambucus black elderberry gummies supplement with Vitamin C and zinc, Kirkland Signature Vitamin D3

This is off the charts, Dr.  increased my Levothyroxine 2 levels from 75 mg to 100  mg.  An ultrasound was also scheduled since Hashimotos Disease means a goiter is present on the thyroid gland. I was diagnosed in 1994. Up to this time, I have NEVER had a TSH level of 24.58. My level has been consistent in the range required or varied slightly. I will be having the TSH level tested again on 4/29/21. Results should be available a couple of days after that. I received the 2nd Covid vaccination on 3/17/21.  The ultrasound on my throat was scheduled on 3/22/21. The results showed significant changes in size of the lymph nods and more importantly the nodule on the right side of the goiter has now increased in size. Prior ultrasounds have shown no change in growth and one test showed a decrease in size of the goiter. The recommndation was to have a CT scan for further evaluation. The CT scan was scheduled on 4/6/21. The results showed the lymph nodes to be reactive which is not a concern. However, the right side nodule on the goiter now requires a fine needle aspiration to send for a biopsy. The fine needle aspiration is scheduled on 4/19/21. The results should be available in approx 5 days (4/23 or 4/26) I have an appointment scheduled with an Endocrinologist to review all test results. This issue can result in necessary surgery to remove the Thyroid gland. I now have difficulty swallow whole food unless chewed thoroughly.  This whole situation has become unsettling and scary.  As I mentioned before  - since 1994 I have never had any issues with growth of a nodule or a TSH level of 24.58

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Five days 18 hours after receiving the Janssen vaccine shot, I awoke with an unusual and very painful headache. I awoke two hours later (about 10:00 AM) with almost unbearable head pain throughout my head, not localized to one area. I drove to fast food restaurant, having a difficult time driving due to pain, and got a half-sweet tea. Tea, having caffeine and some sugar, can often relieve a headache. It didn't offer the relief I expected and about 30 minutes later, I vomited up the tea. I was at that same time ordering a sandwich and detox smoothie, thinking the detox smoothie may help. It seemed to after a couple more hours, but I continued to feel like the headache was still barely there and waiting to return. I ate very well and clean all day, but even late in the evening, I cod feel remnants of a headache. The next morning, 4/12, I awoke again with that same horrible headache, but maybe just slightly less excruciating than the day before. I did not vomit. After a few hours of eating, drinking water, and taking aspirin with Tylenol, the headache subsided.

A neurologist came into explain the results and all tests were negative, but I was diagnosed with Fibral Muscular Dysplasia, but because they didn?t have enough data, he couldn?t say that it was because of the Moderna vaccine. I was released 24 hours later. My BP went back to normal 120/70 3 days later.

On Thursday, April 8, 2021, between 915 and 945 AM, I received the Janssen/Johnson & Johnson single dose COVID-19 Vaccine. As I have had adverse reactions to vaccines in the past, I was advised to wait at the vaccination site for 30 minutes after receiving the vaccine, and I did. Approximately 2 hours after receiving the vaccine in my left arm, I developed a red lacey-type rash all over my body. (This rash still persists today, Tuesday, April 13, 2021 at 3:37 PM and is relieved temporarily with consistent doses of Benadryl capsules, liquid or tablets.)  On Thursday night (April 8), after receiving the vaccine, I began to have body aches and to feel fatigued around 7:30 PM. I took 50 mg Benadryl, 500 mg acetaminophen, 800mg ibuprofen and went to bed. I woke around 12:30 AM and was drenched in sweat and my clothes were wet with sweat. I urinated and went back to bed and was shivering uncontrollably from the time I got out of bed until I got back in the bed and bundled up?it was several minutes before the shivering stopped and I went back to sleep. At approximately 2 AM, I woke up to urinate again. I had a terrible headache, like my head was in a vice; my tongue, throat, and nasal passages were very swollen, and it was difficult to breathe through my nose at all. I took an additional 50 mg of Benadryl and a 500mg acetaminophen and went back to bed. On Friday morning I woke to a phone call from work checking on me. I had slept through all of my alarms and it was 8:35 AM. I was unable to report to work that day and went back to sleep and slept for most of the day, only getting up occasionally to get a drink and use the bathroom. That evening I was able to get up and do a few things with the children and run to the grocery store, however, I became very fatigued and went to bed early without eating dinner.  On Saturday morning, when I woke up, I realized that I had slept for over 12 hours. I was groggy and fatigued all day and had a nap in the afternoon. That evening I was able to participate in family movie night and was feeling ok until about 10 PM. At that time, I began to feel very nauseated and had diarrhea, even though I had not eaten anything that would upset my stomach. I had intense abdominal cramping and felt like I would vomit if I moved around too much. I went to bed and had to get up to use the bathroom with diarrhea at least twice after the initial symptoms at about 10 PM.  On Sunday morning, I woke up after sleeping approximately 10 hours and was able to get up without feeling too fatigued. I did chores and errands and began to feel fatigued in the afternoon and took a nap for about 2 hours. That evening I also had to rush to the bathroom with diarrhea, however, there was no nausea. I went to bed at about 10 PM. On Monday morning, when I woke up, I felt very groggy and did not feel like I had gotten enough sleep. By the evening on Monday, however, I had begun to feel a little less fatigued and more clear-headed. As of Tuesday, April 13, 2021, I have had the red lacey-looking rash intermittently since having the vaccine. I am already on several OTC allergy medications for seasonal allergies and continue to take those medications, however, I have increased my Benadryl intake from 25 mg in the morning to 50 mg in the mornings with 25 -50 mg every 6 hours or so, as well. The rash improves for a short time while I am taking the Benadryl, but it reappears within a few hours after taking the Benadryl.
LAB_DATA: none; was advised by a physician that the rash was a typical reaction and not to worry
OTHER_MEDS: benadryl 50 mg, zyrtec 10 mg tablet, flonase nasal spray, pataday eye drops, 500 mg acetaminophen, 800mg ibuprofen
CUR_ILL: BV, bacterial infection for which I am on suppression dosing; I did not have a dose within 24 hours prior to, or following the vaccination.
ALLERGIES: macrobid (nitrofurantoin), corn, seasonal and plant/tree/flower pollen, animals (cat, dog, horse, vermin)

In office patient evaluation performed 27 days after patient received J & J covid vaccine at a vaccine site.   Symptoms at presentation were:  4 week history of post vaccine fatigue, decreased stamina, exertion related tachycardia, and dyspnea on exertion.  Patient is a regular exerciser  with a high fitness level. Exam was unrevealing. Lab testing included CBC CMP thyroid profile ESR C-reactive protein Lyme titers and D-dimer.  All were normal/negative.    The reportable lab findings were:  SARS-COV-2 IgM and IgG antibody titers were zero on the initial evaluation.  Six days later SARS-COV-2 IgG, IgM, and IgA titers were done at Lab.  All titers were zero.  So 4 and 5 weeks after receiving the J & J vaccine, this patient had no antibody response.  He has no underlying disease process known to me to explain this finding.  My concern is possible administration of faulty J & J vaccine which may have been distributed before the manufacturing error was identified.

- 22 year-old female  - Tested positive for COVID-19 on January 31, 2021. My symptoms lasted 21 days and started with major gastrointestinal issues, headache, and cough.  - Had a negative COVID-19 PCR test on February 25, 2021  - this negative PCR was needed to travel back. - Landed on February 28, 2021 and completed my quarantine at my parents house.  - I returned to work on the 15th of March, 2021.  - Over the weekend I traveled and flew back on April 5, 2021. Because I had flown, I was doing a courtesy and went to the local store to get a rapid antigen test.  APRIL 8, 2021 - left work at 12:30 and went to the store to get the rapid antigen test which came back positive. I was told by the nurses that it only came back positive because it has been less than 90 days since I initially tested positive. I was told I did not need to self-isolate and could go about as normal. I had my second dose of the Moderna vaccine on this day at 2:00 p.m. I went to get my second jab. Just to be safe, after my jab I went to the local urgent care where they took a nasal swab for a PCR test. The results of the PCR test came back Saturday, April 10 about 7:30 that evening and the result was "NOT DETECTED".  SYMPTOMS: Thursday, April 8th  about 8:00 pm I started to have difficulty breathing and taking a deep breath was difficult. I put it down to anxiety about the initial positive test. Saturday, the difficulty breathing continued, along with new pressure in my chest. I was unable to sleep Saturday night - as soon as I was nearly sleep, I would wake up gasping for a breath. Sunday, the pressure in my chest continued and so did the difficulty breathing. I went to the Emergency Room on Sunday, April 11 about 4:15 pm - they took a chest x-ray, ran blood tests, and did an EKG which all came back completely normal - no pneumonia, heart attack, or blood clots. The doctor gave me a 1 mg dose of an anti-anxiety medicine because he could tell I was very stressed. He later prescribed me Prednisone (3 tablets a day for 4 days). As of today, I am still having a very hard time taking a full, deep breath and continue to have pressure in my chest.

Woke up about 8:00am on 3/28/21 with a fever of 102.6, stiff neck, chills, nausea, headache.  Continued with Tylenol throughout day.  For 3 days I had all of those symptoms plus diarrhea. I assumed this was normal but was getting concerned because I had no symptoms from the first vaccine on 3/5/21.  I never got a stiff or painful arm but I did get a rash on my arm face and neck starting on 3/31/21.  The rash continues on my neck, face and shoulder intermittently to date, more than 2 weeks later.  On 3/31/21 about 12 noon my fever had gone down to 99.0.  Every time I would get out of bed my fever would spike immediately to 101 or 102.  On 4/1/21 I called the nurse through my insurance company and she said to stop taking the Tylenol and if the fever continued to go to Urgent Care on 4/2/21, which is what I did.  They performed a rapid Covid test which was negative and my fever was normal but my blood pressure was quite high which is not normal for me.  I had nausea, headache, fatigue, sore muscles.  They really didn't tell me what to do and said my reaction to the vaccine was "normal" and they didn't know how long it would last.  It is now more than 2 weeks after the vaccine and I do not feel great.  Although the fever has gone away I still have the intermittent rash, nausea, diarrhea, stiff neck.  The soonest I could get an appointment with my Primary Care doctor is 3/27/21.  I am concerned because I have the gene mutation Prothombin 20210A (Factor 2) which is  a clotting disorder.  In 2010 I was hospitalized and almost died from a massive DVT and PE in both lungs.  I did not know until I was admitted to hospital that I had this clotting disorder.  I am also a Colo-rectal cancer survivor and had radiation and chemotherapy along with several surgeries in 2013.  I have been NED since.  Given today's news about blood clotting problems with the Janssen vaccine (although I had Pfizer) I just wanted to report my side effects since I have a blood clotting disorder.

My limbs still felt weak when seated and my blood pressure was better but not normal yet, so I was told to lay down a bit longer. Since leaving the clinic, I haven't had any abnormal side effects or reactions.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: at about 4 hours after vaccine I thought I was having a stroke. The right side of my face went numb and felt like it was drooping, my right arm went numb, my right leg and foot went numb. But I could still talk and make a smile face so I did not go to ER. Gradually both of my legs became very weak and then my hands became very weak. This lasted for over a week/ten days. By the first night I couldn't sleep because my brain could not seem to get into a deep sleep pattern, had body aches and sore arm but not dreadful, and by the next day had a fever which maxed at 101 degrees ( my normal is 97.2-97.4). Had a low grade fever for 10 days! Also by the 2nd day I had swollen glands in my right neck and armpit, and pain from my  right elbow to my neck. My usual level of unstable balance was MUCH worse for at least a week and my usual tinnitus was MUCH louder than usual for about 10 days! Night 3 I had a very bad episode of something like restless leg which also extended not just in my legs but also into my head! Very bizarre! By day 4 I was having episodes of near fainting, often. This lasted for about another week. All in all it was a dreadful experience, which I believe was related to issues with my already compromised nervous system due to the Parkinson's/MSA. I will NEVER have another one fetes vaccines or booster shots if those become available. I am quite frightened that the next vaccine could result in me actually having a stroke or other serious consequence.

As described above, about 13 hours after the vaccine I woke up at 3 am with a severe pounding and constant headache. I was also extremely fatigued so much so that I did not get out of bed or do anything all day 4/11 and didn't start feeling better until the following Monday. Then I hear in the news about the 6 adverse reactions and the J&J vaccine shutdown, possibility for blood clots etc. and to keep an eye out for various symptoms over next 2-3 weeks! It was stressful enough registering and not being able to secure the Moderna or Pfizer so I just said ok and got the J&J. Now I have something else to worry about. Heart and blood clot issues are in my family. I do not take any blood thinners and don't plan to. But now am questioning whether I should have gotten the vaccine at all. I have had enough chronic illness in my life. In fact, December 2019 I was in another town taking care of my mother and her subsequent death when I caught someone's cough. Urgent care diagnosed me with pneumonia, fluid in the lungs, put me on course of antibiotics. I couldn't breathe, needed a nebulizer etc. They called me and said it was not pneumonia or flu a or b (I get the shot every year) and to go to the ER if it got worse. I couldn't eat or move much for three weeks and breathing was extremely difficult. I had to get a nebulizer. Eventually went away. Then in March Covid 19 became official. When I tested for Covid 19 here at a state site in 2021, I tested negative.

This was not reported to my Dr. but I felt it needed to be report to FDA.  My symptoms began around 3 am (~13 hours after injection, early Saturday morning) with joint and muscle aches and pains along with injection site pain and slight nausea.  I took  tylenol 2-500 mg capsules at ~4:30 am.   Severe chills started around 8 am.  I took tylenol 2-500 mg capsules at 10 am and went to  sleep covered in blankets to try to keep warm.  I woke up around 1:45pm sweating and very warm.  I took my temperature and it was 101.8F.  My "normal" is around 97.7F.  This worried me very much since I was on tylenol. I made sure to drink plenty of water (iced).   The fever dropped to 100F around 6 pm and stayed there.  I could not take more tylenol due to stomach upset.   The fever continued into the second day (Sunday)post-injection staying around 99-100F without tylenol.     By later Sunday, the aches and pains had subsided significantly.  Sunday night I had more bouts of chills with fever off and on all night.  This continued into Monday all day.  By Monday night, i was feeling more normal.   Had I not been feeling better I would have sought medical care.  I am left with slight nausea and an acid-y feeling stomach today, Tuesday. I am a DVM who has worked in the pharmaceutical and medical device industry and wanted to express my concern with this type of reaction to a vaccine.  In my humble opinion having a vaccine that causes a person to be sick for nearly 3 days after is unacceptable!  If it weren't for the pandemic, I don't think this would be approved due to the severity of the reaction.  The mRNA platform should not be  used due to the known effects of causing cytokine release which can lead to these severe reactions.  We need to find something better!
OTHER_MEDS: Metoprolol, eliquis, trazodone, armour thyroid, venlafaxine, multi-vitamin, vitamin C, omega-3s, calcium, magnesium,
HISTORY: atrial fibrilation treated for breast cancer-in remission

Less than 12 hours after the vaccination I woke up at 1 a.m. with severe chills and body aches, a 102 fever and terrible headache.  The worst of this lasted 5 or 6 hours and slowly improved, although I could not get back to sleep. I was out of commission for the entire day.   At 6 p.m that evening my temperature was still at 100 degrees and the headache remained.  The following day, April 8th, I did feel better. I was still fatigued and only then did I notice any pain/sensitivity at the injection site (I think the body aches masked anything less severe). This pain was to be expected and nothing out of the ordinary. I am fine now. I was taken aback at the severity of the adverse reaction.  Also, my 20-year-old son got the shot at the same place -- with the same Lot Number 043A21A -- and had exactly the same reactions as I did. (They even started one hour after mine -- the same amount of time our injections were spaced out).    (He may not be reporting it.  Being only 20, he's not as thorough with these things although I will try to get him to do so).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received the COVID vaccine (Pfizer, lot # ER8731, expiration date 7/2021) at 11:15. Client  walked up to the EMT desk and reported dizziness and blurry vision, EMT and RN responded at 11:28. The client returned to her seat, ambulating with a steady gait, no visible distress, color normal. Vital signs obtained: blood pressure 122/78, heart rate 88, respiratory rate 12, O2 level 99%. Client stated she experiences these symptoms before she gets a migraine. The client stated that migraines are her only medical condition, she has no prescribed medications and no allergies. The client was alert and oriented and had no difficulty breathing. The client stated she hadn't eaten yet and just had a drink of water at 0740. She refused water and benadryl. At 1133, the client stated that she felt "totally fine" and wanted to leave. Encouraged the client to stay for 30 minutes from her symptom onset but she deferred. Education provided regarding mobile reporting system, emergency management and AMR activation, and primary care follow up. Client denied questions and left at that time, ambulated with a steady gait to her car.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 8 days after vaccination, in the morning of April 6th, 2021 my left arm started to feel sore and tender around the injection site and there was a small rash forming. This rash lasted 3 days and then went away.  The evening of April 11th, I noticed the skin on my upper left arm was warm to the touch again but no rash was visible at the time.  The morning of April 12th, 2021 a large rash appeared covering the majority of my upper arm again.  Same as before, my upper arm was tender and the rash was burning, itched, was warm, firm and raised.  It is now April 13th and the rash is still present, but diminishing.  It is no longer tender or burning but does still itch occasionally.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was scheduled for second dose at appropriate interval 28 days from first dose 3/30 to come back on 4/27. Patient presented 4/13 on day 14 since she thought the next appointment was 2 weeks, not 4 weeks. Patient bypassed the screening process and this was not caught by registration or vaccination. Patient was called after the error was discovered and her primary care provider was also informed of the situation.
Onset next day Chills. Fever,  body aches,  joint pain,  abdominal pain,  left breast swelled to double the size

by 10-11 p.m. that night severe chills. did not sleep the entire night due to extreme headache, chills, fever (102+), body aches.  felt truly awful.     by 6 am Saturday feeling nauseated and wound up vomiting. Saturday night/Sunday -- not 100%, no appetite, intermittent nausea, but able to work/do normal activities. Monday 4/5--nausea at an 8-9 in the morning and kept a trash can next to me during virtual hearings I had that day.   Intermittent nausea throughout the week and not much appetite but made sure I was eating/drinking despite that.   Wednesday night 4/7 -- I went to use a PT stick on my left leg b/c I had felt a little pain in my left knee and figured my quadriceps were fibrotic.  I could barely put any pressure on my left thigh. I had never experienced anything like this.  As soon as I started rolling the stick on my leg, my skin was immediately red and warm and my leg was so sore and tender I had to stop.   Saturday 4/10 -- woke up with severe headache and later that morning felt very weird in my head/heart, like heart racing and my head felt "spinny."  Felt like I might pass out at one point so I had one of my kids sit on my bed with me until I felt a little better. Sunday 4/11 -- had another episode like Saturday (headache and lightheaded/spinny/pass out feeling/slow speech) and asked neighbor (an RN) to take my BP.  her at-home device said 147 over something and she suggested I go to urgent care just to double check.   About three hours later, I was seen at  urgent care.  BP was normal, heart rate normal, oxygen was 96.  4/13--followed up with primary doctor.  Send me for blood work to check platelets, etc.  Feeling pretty good today but nervous after the news and the pause.

May not be related to vaccine, but 9 days after I developed itching on balls of feet. Next day developed rash on left hand (palm side), with severe itching (nothing on  right hand). Also found there to be an unusual amount of itching  all over body. over the course of the rash. Lasted about 5-6 days.  No rash appeared on arm at all (i.e., "Covid Arm")

It is now the next day, and I feel significantly better. I have pain at the injection site, some muscle fatigue, a little bit of a depleted appetite, tiredness in my eyes and head (likely due to lack of quality sleep), and a bit of sweating, but my pain has reduced to maybe a 2/10 or 1/10 (i.e., not even uncomfortable). I did end up getting decent sleep between 2 AM and 12 PM with only a few interruptions of family members checking on me. The only notable pain that is worrying me is abnormal soreness in my right wrist that is not the result of overuse, overextension, etc., although I was able to take care of that pain with another 3 Advil pills. I am considering scheduling a doctor's appointment, as I know the J&J vaccine got recalled today for blood clots. My assumption is that because I am a healthy 20-year-old, my immune system overreacted to the vaccine, but I want to check to make sure that it doesn't cause any additional health problems.
OTHER_MEDS: Zoloft 50mg daily; Tylenol at 5pm for headache; Advil at 10pm for pain.

Obviously I have no idea if this was due to the vaccine or not but it seems very coincidental that this would happen for the first time in my life within two weeks of getting the shot,  I still plan to get the second shot but will avoid shellfish for some time.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hello, I received my J&J vaccine on 3/31/2021. 11:00a.m. Here is my results:  3/31/21 Day1: Waited 30 mins at site due to the history of Penicillin and Sulfa issues in the past. I had a little headache. 4/2/21 Day 3: Morning was slow.  I noticed that I was tired.  Headache was stronger.  I took Ibuprofen 400mg. By mid day, I was on the couch the rest of the day.  My body was telling me to rest.  So I did.  4/2/21 Day 3: Morning was slow.  I noticed that I was tired.  Headache was stronger.  I took Ibuprofen 400mg. By mid day, I was on the couch the rest of the day.  My body was telling me to rest.  So I did. 4/3/21 Day 4: Morning was extremely slow.  I did force myself to get up at the normal time, but I didn't want to.  Headache was still present.  Body sluggish.  I ran an errand for about an hour, and when I returned, I was exhausted, so I took a 3 hour nap.  Headache all day.  Took Ibuprofen 400mg. 4/4/21 Day 5: Headache had gone away.  Today I noticed that I had a rash on my mid to lower back.  We put some cortisone cream on it, and it helped.  I have clear skin and don't normally have any reactions to anything. Very tired 4/5/21 Day 6: Feeling pretty good today.  The rash is still there and itching, but the cream is helping.  I feel like I am 80% back to my normal self. 4/6/21 Day 7: Almost back to normal.  Rash has almost cleared up, and I have my energy back to about 90%. Still a very slight headache. 4/7/21 Day 8:  Still having a slight headache. Skipped from 4/7-13th/21 - Doing much better. Still having a slight headache here and there.  Noticing that I am very tired in the afternoon, and making myself take a nap.

Then she laid me down on my back and tilted my head off the table and I had the worse dizziness ever, but no nystagmus.  She sat me up.  My BP jumped to 190/100; pulse 100.  I couldn't stop being dizzy. Paramedics took me to emergency room.   After 2 hours the doctor performed the Epley Maneuver, but there was no nystagmus so it wasn't BPPV.  Had CT scan and MRI and everything was clear.  What changed and what may have caused all this was that I had the J&J vaccine prior to all the dizziness.

Three days later, on 3/7/21, you began to have fatigue, shortness of breath, dizziness and chest pressure. Because all symptoms continued for 24 hours, on the evening of 3/8/21, you took yourself to the Emergency Department.  Your ER work-up included a CXR (negative), an EKG (showing a left bundle branch block), serum bloodwork (negative for MI), however, the D-dimer and spiral CT were both positive for a pulmonary emboli (i.e. a blood clot in your lungs).  You were admitted to the hospital and started on the blood thinner, Eliquis.  During your 3-day hospital stay, your work-up also included a bilateral lower extremity Doppler study (negative) and an echocardiogram (showing left ventricular hypertrophy).  You were discharged on all of your previously prescribed medications (see list below), except for the fish oil.  You were also started on Eliquis.  Since discharge, you have followed up with your PCP and have been referred to a cardiologist and pulmonologist.  To date, you have had no further symptoms. I also noticed that I wasn?t sweating very much/at all until about a week after I received the vaccine, which was very worrying. I attempted to drink plenty of water during all of this, though I can?t be sure I succeeded. I think my menstrual period may have happened during this week, maybe starting on the Tuesday falling the vaccine, but cannot remember for sure. Constipation and dehydration are unusual for my period, though the pain is not. There was soreness in my arm muscles around the vaccine site, but it was consistent with what I feel from any other vaccine, and only lasted a day.  All discomfort ceased about a week after the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I administered the Moderna vaccine (LOT 007B21A, EXP 9/8/21) on 4/13/21 @ 2:13pm and asked the patient to remain seated in her chair for at least 15 minutes. Approximately after 5 minutes, my technician noticed that the patient was pale and immediately flagged me. I stopped what I was doing and immediately checked on the patient. She stated that she was feeling nauseas. The patient appeared to be sweating. We grabbed an ice pack and garbage can. Within approximately a minute, the patient started vomiting 3 or 4 times over a period of approximately 5 minutes. We applied cold compresses to patient's neck and face. The patient started to feel better as time progressed. Patient stated that she did not eat much for lunch (chips), felt a little anxious, and felt a little warm/hot before getting the vaccination (she had on a rain jacket). I contacted pharmacy market manager. We checked her blood pressure and it was 120/90 with 93 pulse. We stayed with the patient and comforted her. She called her husband to come pick her up. She thanked the both of us. We were very thankful that the patient was safe and never fell off her chair or injured herself. I called her about 45 minutes after she left the club to check up on her and she mentioned that she feels perfectly fine now.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received the 1st dose of COVID vaccine by Pfizer lot # EW0161 and expiration date: 4/17/2021 at 11:37am. At 11:50am client reported to EMT that she felt dizzy. Client reports not feeling okay and really dizzy like she is going to faint and hotness on her eyes. PHN offer client water. Client has no medical conditions and takes no medications and has never had a reaction to any vaccine before. Client reports she is not pregnant.  Other PHN arrived to assist at 11:52 am able to get oxygen: 100% and pulse: 82. Shortly after client reports she needs to throw up, provided emesis bag and client vomits X 2.  Right after client vomited color returned to her lips. At 12PM vitals are pulse: 70, blood pressure: 138/79.  At 12:05pm pulse: 64 and blood pressure 120/82, client reports no headache, no blurred vision and no nausea.  Nurse went outside to get husband and son of client and walked them over to client.  At 12:15pm pulse was 62 and blood pressure 116/78, client reports feeling tired, no pain, no nausea and no headache.  At 12:25pm client vitals were pulse: 60, blood pressure 120/80.  Client left facility with a steady gait at 12:28pm.

I then made myself a tea with ginger, turmeric, cayenne pepper, black pepper, lemon peel, lemon juice, coconut oil and honey. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine EUA.  The vaccine was given at 10:45 AM. At 4:00 PM I began feeling nauseous. At 9:00 or 10:00 PM I began feeling both muscle and joint pain on my upper body which made it somewhat difficult to sleep. After one or two hours of sleep at 1:00 AM I woke up with a fever, headache, and worse muscle and joint pain (upper body only). When I woke up I was sweating profusely that the bed was lightly wet and extremely hot from all the heat my body was letting go. An ice pack can relieve the headache and fever. However, I was still not able to sleep. At 4:00 AM I made the decision to consume 800 mg of ibuprofen and it took 20 minutes for my headache and fever to go away. Yet, after being able to sleep for 30 minutes, I woke up again to the same headache and fever. Around 10:00 AM the symptoms were partly gone and was finally able to get sleep after a long night.

I did not eat dinner because there was no appetite.  I slept in bed for at least 12 hours.  Typical night sleep = 8 hours.  The next morning was no issue and therefore I did not go seek medical help because there are supposed to be side effects to vaccines.  Now, I am reporting it because headache and the stiff muscles were identified on the news.  However, it was around 24-36 hours and not the 6 days on the news.

I did not mention it to the pharmacist since I figured it was normal. I sat for 15 minutes as instructed, but  other than feeling sore, I was normal. So we left. After about another 15 mins, My head started for feel "drunk". I contemplated pulling over since I was driving home, but decided to get home asap.  As time went by, my head felt more and more cloudy, fuzzy, heavy and as if I'd been drinking alcohol. That night, I couldn't sleep. I even took hydrocodon with tylenol (the pain was that bad) and an ibprofin. It helped a little. I finally got to sleep at 3am, Just to wake at 7am for work. All day, I could not focus, my head was super fuzzy. I had a bad headache, I felt super sick. My stomach also hurt and I couldn't lift my arm. I tried taking a nap half way through the day because I kept making mistakes at work. It did not help how I felt. Since then, my symptoms have eased but now I seem to have a bad case of acid reflux, which I didn't used to get randomly.   I have not been to my dr yet and I haven't done anything else for it. I was informed that I should report my symptoms by a family friend.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pfizer Covid 19 vaccine: hives/broke out in hives/received the shot on her right arm, but the hives spread on the left shoulder down the arm and forearm; she still has "lizard skin"; has nerve on back shoulder to side and back of arm to forearm to her thumb which is not spasming; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 79-year-old female patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), via an unspecified route of administration, administered in right arm on 30Jan2021 (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as single dose for covid-19 immunisation. Medical history included allergic to penicillin and bee stings. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. The patient previously had flu vaccine and had a flu and shingles vaccine and had shingles for 3 weeks after she took the shingles vaccine. The patient received her first vaccine on 30Jan2021. On 31Jan2021, the patient ended up in ER with hives from the vaccine. She was told that she would be given Prednisone for hives but not to take it until Monday at noon. Stated that they wanted her to wait 48 hours after vaccine before she started it because it would cut it in half. She started Prednisone 40mg on Monday and did get a few more hives on Tuesday and Wednesday. She had the shot in her right arm, and all this happened on the left side of her back. She had a patch of hive of 5x6 to 8x8 on her back and on the back of her arm by her elbow and forearm. She put apple cider vinegar on her arms, and she did not itch anymore. Someone told her that this could be shingles. She stated that she got flu vaccine and got sick with flu and she took the shingles vaccine and got shingles. She could not stand in shower with the shingles but that she can with this, so she knows that it is not the shingles. The patient did not want to take the second shot on 20Feb2021 and wanted to know what Pfizer thinks. She does like to travel and hopes to soon so she wanted to know if not taking the shot could get a stipulation if they required two shots to travel. She has nerve on back shoulder to side and back of arm to forearm to her thumb which is not spasming, but she knows that it is there which came on in the past week (2021). She was on Prednisone 40 mg for 5 days and she still had hives (though they are diminishing). The patient stated that she still has "lizard skin". She received the shot on her right arm, but the hives spread on the left shoulder down the arm and forearm where she had shingles. Her ER doctor told her not to take the second dose and her primary care physician told her to wait and think about it. She is wondering if she should receive the second dose. The outcome of the event hives was not recovered while the other events was unknown.  Information on the Batch/Lot number has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe headache that woke me from sleep at 15 hours post vaccination; then at 24 hours post vaccination, typical side effects began with chills, aches and tiredness.  However, at 28 hours post vaccination, my fever climbed to 102.  I had such severe body aches, I needed assistance to get up and was nearly impossible to walk or move. I had no appetitie. I decided to take 2 extra strength tylenol to aid in the fever/chills and severe headache.  Unfortunately, two days prior to vaccine, I was diagnosed by CT scan that I had a kidney stone.  It was being treated with Toradol, which I only took at bedtime with the also, prescribed Flomax.  The Toradol did little to assuage my body aches, incidentally  My fever only came down to 101.4 .  It remained between 101.4 and 102 until 48 hours post vaccination, when it finally went down to 99.2.  I could only get out of bed to use the bathroom.  I drank at least 2.25L of water daily because I was flushing a kidney stone, so my fluid intake was very strong.   I knew that many of my friends/relatives have had the 2nd shot, so I messaged with them, but nobody had had a fever over 102.  I knew if I did not take anything, it would've easily been 103F. I'd consider myself general recovered from the worst of the fever, body aches and fatigue.

Transported to ER.  Called patient next day to check on her.  Reports in ER given IV steroids, sent home on PO steroids and an epinephrine pen.  Told not to get second dose of vaccine.  Patient states hasn't had any problems since.  Never had a rash or swelling or trouble breathing.

Me history of allergies. Medical history of lupus and kidney problems secondary to lupus. Current medication: Myfortic and lisinopril. PHN assessed for face flushing and swelling. Client able to answer all questions with no problem and denied shortness of breath. Client informed we could keep 30 mins for further observation. Vitals at 1448: blood pressure: 130/90, pulse 75, oxygen 97%. Client stated sensation returning and smaller area affected now. Denied shortness of breath, no redness or swelling noted. Vitals at 1358: blood pressure: 130/80, pulse 79, oxygen 99%. Per client more improvement. Client advised to speak with provider before second dose. Last vitals at 1408: blood pressure: 126/80, pulse 70, oxygen 98%. Per client sensation almost back completely. Affected area only tip of nose and maxillary sinus area. Client stated well to leave facility. Per client family member waiting outside and would be driving. ER precautions given. Client left facility at 1411 with steady gait.

Description of Error: Patient presented at vaccination table after having documents and appointment reviewed by non-clinical staff, and identity was confirmed by RN Vaccinator using two unique identifiers (including DOB). Nurse vaccinator reviewed patient's responses to screening form completed and screened patient to confirm she was feeling well, had no history of anaphylaxis, does not carry an epi-pen for allergies, and had not received COVID vaccine previously. Nurse vaccinator educated patient on possible side effects of Moderna product. Patient indicated she wished to be immunized, received Moderna vaccine, and proceeded to observation area where she waited for fifteen minutes before departing from clinic without reporting any adverse event. Patient was later found to be 12 months (dose received on 17th birthday) under the minimum age of 18 years for receiving Moderna COVID-19 vaccine, thereby rendering the medication as administered outside the age limit of the applicable order.   Immediate Action/Intervention: Patient was under observation for CDC-mandated 15-minute period following vaccine administration. Upon review of records and discovery that dose was administered to patient who was 12 months too young to be eligible. Director of Nursing was informed of error and tasked with completing required documentation and performed root cause analysis.  Corrective Action by Individual & Program: RN vaccinator has identified need for including review of patient?s age during screening performed prior to every vaccine administration as necessary redundancy in the interest of patient safety in case ineligible patient is not correctly identified during clinic check-in process.  Director of Nursing/Chief Planning, COVID will ensure that signage is available throughout the clinic stating minimum age for vaccine and ensure that there is an announcement at each trainings prior to the start of each clinic.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: April 7th about 6:30pm: I became very confused, having trouble remembering where I was or answering simple questions.  Around that same time my vision became blurry, and my face in and around my mouth became numb, I began to slur as a result.  The numbness and slurring increased over the next hour or so.  After that hour or so, I realized I was exhausted and my head hurt so I went to sleep. I also had a strange emotional response to all of this, I behaved giddily and as though it were funny.  April 8th about 8am: I woke up and the confusion, blurry vision, numbness, and slurring were gone.  I had a mild headache, brain fog, and was still more tired than usual.  Later that evening the headache developed in to something more like a migraine, intense pain focused behind my right eye and blurred vision.  At this time I again decided to go to sleep.  It would have been about 8pm.  April 9th about 8am: I woke up still feeling a moderate headache focused on the right side, still tired, and brain fog.  The symptoms weakened throughout the day and by the evening I was feeling mostly normal again.   I have felt healthy and normal since.
LAB_DATA: I did not seek any testing or treatment for my symptoms.  At the time they occurred my husband called the pharmacy and urgent care to inquire if my reaction was expected or not; both the pharmacy and urgent care informed us that they were normal side effects and not to worry.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: While walking a patient from urgent care to radiology at approximately 1632 on 4/12/21, I witnessed another patient (patient affected by event) fall to the floor by the pharmacy window. I rushed to the patient's side and began an initial assessment of airway, breathing, and circulation. No active bleeding or head injury detected. The patient was lying to her right side and appeared to be unconscious. No response when called or tapped on the shoulder several times. Patient's eyes appeared to be half-open without apparent movement. I asked for assitance from nearby security officer to call an ERT. Approximately 30-45 seconds into event, patient's daughter appeared on scene and attempted to call patient without response. While daughter assisted with supporting the patient's head, the patient suddenly took a deep breath and appeared to blink eyes several times (approx 5 seconds) before returning to previous unconscious state. No response when called by daughter throughout event. Another staff member appeared on scene at this time and recorded the second unconsciousness episode, which lasted for 90 seconds. ERT, urgent care providers, and other staff members were on scene at this time. 911 called. Vital signs taken and further assessments conducted. A pillow was placed under the patient's head and cervical collar applied. Patient appeared to be confused and in and out of consciousness at this moment. Patient was not able to identify name, date of birth, or current location but did state she had pain in her neck when asked in Spanish by another urgent care staff member. 911 staff on site at approximately 1645. Patient left in stable condition via ambulance gurney to higher level of care, accompanied by daugher and  paramedics.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 29 y/o F w no sig past medical history who now presents with a maculopapular rash around her injection site 1 week after Moderna mRNA covid vaccine that then spread to her trunk/chest. Initially pt was advised to pretreat before her second dose, but a web-based consult was done in the interim with the following advice: This doesn?t appear to be an immediate type allergic reaction. Benadryl would not be expected to prevent a reaction. I do have some concern about a second dose having the potential to induce a much more intense reaction. This one is very atypical but doesn?t appear to be insignificant. Unless the patient has very significant risk factors for a severe case of COVID, I would refrain from a second dose. There is nothing wrong in continuing cetirizine if it helps with current itching. A second opinion on the web-based eConsult service yielded the following: Having a delayed reaction is not a contraindication toward getting the 2nd dose. However, I see 1 vesicular/bullous lesion on her rash, which is concerning as the next dose may develop into bullous dermatitis or SJS. In this case, I would definitely encourage patient getting the J&J vaccine given that patient had reaction towards mRNA one. If patient does get the 2nd dose of mRNA vaccine, I would recommend it on the other arm. I would tell her to start taking cetirizine 1 tablet twice daily for 1-2 weeks, and I would also prescribe her topical Triamcinolone twice daily to put on when rash erupts. Having anaphylaxis would be unlikely, but I would still prescribe her an epinephrine autoinjector to be on the cautious side since some people have mixed drug reactions (both type 1 and type 4). I would wait until her symptoms fully resolve before she gets the J&J vaccine. Given that she had a reaction to a prior COVID vaccine, I would prescribe epipen just in case even if she gets J&J. Again, highly unlikely she would react with anaphylaxis but it's always good to be safe. will send pt epipen and give counseling as above.  Allergist #1 response: I think above is reasonable. Reasonable regarding giving J&J. I would not give second dose of Moderna.
OTHER_MEDS: Fluticasone Propionate 50 MCG/ACT Suspension Nasal sig: 1 spray intranasally in each nostril, twice daily MVI Neilmed Sinus Rinse Complete sig: use twice per day as directed

With prior vaccines and flu shots, I have either had no side effects or mild.  But with the COVID vaccine, I was sicker than sick!  I wasn't expecting to miss as much work as I did, nor go to the doctor three times in a week's time.  I received it around 11:30am on Thursday, March 18.  Around 1pm, my mild headache started to intensify and had ringing in my ears that would repeatedly come and go (still is doing so today, just not as frequent).  Around 4pm is when all of the "normal" side effects started?chills, hot flashes, sore arm, and super sleepy.  I woke up a couple hours later, with a headache that was WAY worse and was super nauseous.   This was close to 10pm.  Then, around 11pm that same night, I developed HORRID shooting ear pains and took my first Tylenol.  The ear/jaw pain was more than I could stand - had it in both ears, but the right ear was more intense.  It felt like I had a lighting rod between both ears and had these intense "zings" that kept going back and forth, like they were playing ping-pong.  The painful "zings" reminded me of those felt during an ear infection but WAY MORE INTENSE.  My jaw was super tight, as well, with a horribly intense headache.  I spent the entire night night doing warm compresses on my ears, taking Tylenol every 4-6 hours, staying in the shower, and lots of crying.  It was so bad that I felt the need to go to the ER but didn't feel comfortable driving and didn't want to go the ambulance route?and thought it was pointless because going to the ER for ear pain would leave me there for hours and hours since I didn't feel it would be viewed an an urgent emergency.  My goal was to make it through the night and see if I could get into my PCP doctor the following morning.  I took another Tylenol around 5am, and I thankfully cried myself to sleep for a couple of hours.  When I woke up, I called my PCP but couldn't get in, so I did an online doctor visit through my insurance company.  My fever was about 103.06 at its highest during the night but was gone by 3:34pm Friday afternoon (assuming because I was taking more Tylenol than I had been post-online doctor's appointment).  Around 7pm Friday evening, I knew I needed to go to the ER or urgent care.  I got a ride and was taken to urgent care for my intense ear pain.  They gave me a Toradol injection and Tramadol prescription.  By bedtime Friday night, the injection was doing its job and made the ear pain and zings were much less intense (didn't get the prescription until a couple days later).  On March 20, Saturday night, is when I developed a red, itchy rash on my back and tummy.  Over the next couple of days, it was on my chest, arms, legs?pretty much come and was in various places.  I called my PCP Monday morning (March 22), left a message, and they called me back to tell me to restart taking my Zyrtec/HCL to see if it would help the itching.  It has and am just mildly breaking out at this time.  The stinkin' ear/jaw pain returned on Tuesday the 23rd, so I loaded up on OTC ear drops and made an appointment with my PCP for Wednesday, March 24.  She saw no ear infection and essentially told me to keep taking the pain meds.  I received the vaccine on March 18 and did not return to work until the following Thursday.  In retrospect, I should have just missed the remainder of that week, too.

HISTORY: Possible fibromyalgia, migraines/post-concussion, gastro motility issues, idiopathic neuropathy, interstitial cystitis

Since he was feeling light-headed, the immunizing pharmacist told me to get the blood pressure cuff. When I got back, the patient passed out. The pharmacist and I moved the chair from underneath him and he gently put him on the floor. He quickly woke up and the pharmacist began to ask him questions such as his name and where he was to make sure he was ok. He was able to answer those questions fine and we placed him in a chair so he can rest. When he was in the chair, he began to pass out again. He quickly woke up again but wasn't feeling good. The pharmacist checked his blood pressure and it was low. His temperature was at 93F. The pharmacist continued to stay with him and he made sure that someone else was able to come and pick him up. Once he felt ok, he had the patient go sit in the post-vaccination waiting area until he had his ride pick him up.
